body: Use dedicated utility code to compare int/float objects based on injected type checks.

comment_data.body:
The other option for deduplicating these (rather than adding `{{type1}}_`{{type2}}` to the name, would be to enclose them in an

```
#ifndef __PYX_COMPARE_FLOAT_INT_{{OP}}_DEFINED
#define __PYX_COMPARE_FLOAT_INT_{{OP}}_DEFINED
// ...
#endif
```

That doesn't let you have different versions of `CYTHON_INLINE` but it does get rid of duplicate code.

â€¦ although the intention for this is to get it inlined in most cases, so there won't be much of an advantage for the binaries in the end. It's still a good idea, there's no need to let the C compiler analyse the function more than once. Thanks.

commit.message: Add special cases for builtin number comparisons of unknown types.
Add missing sign check for Py<3.12.
Revert to previous int-compare implementation, with fixes.
Add a generated test for all type combinations of interesting values.
Fix rough bucket check for int/float comparison and apply it to both comparisons.
Fix and implement handling of float NaN and inf.

Rename test to avoid running it in Python.
It directly compares to Python doctest results anyway.
Remove empty comment lines from generated C utility code.
Avoid PyObject_RichCompareBool() where we may risk comparing objects that do not compare equal despite identity (specifically NaN).
Refactor comparison code into separate functions that can be inlined independently.
Move None tests more out of the way.
Always evaluate comparisons as bint if that is the expected result.
Remove "is_pycmp" flag from comparison nodes and instead always rely on the node type.
Avoid unused code and unused labels.
Tune integer comparisons for small integers.
Extract the relatively long running comparison benchmarks into a new benchmark file to separate them from the short-running Cython feature benchmarks.
Implement int-int comparison for the Limited API.
Implement float-int comparison for the Limited API.
Limit fast int-float comparison to safe exact value range (2**53).

title: Special case Python comparisons of int/float objects
